<br>
Seriously, great discussion on this.  First, I do think raid leaders/organizers have the right to set whatever rules they want.  As long as people know those rules up front and can make an informed decision, it just comes down to a personal decision on the part of each player as to whether they can accept and live with those rules.  Now, that leader may have zero people show up for the event if the rules are ludicrous, but you still have the freedom to do that.  So in that aspect I do support Azrok's right to make whatever rules he wants, just as Shy and I have done for our Alliance raids.  <br>
<br>
As Shy and I researched and talked over many weeks about Sidi and just raids in general, we really spent a lot of time talking about loot.  In both of our opinions, the way in which loot is handled can make or break your reputation as a leader (and perhaps your guild) as well as cast a shadow over the whole raid.  For example, you zip through Sidi and kill Apoc - wow!!  People are pumped, it's exciting, great teamwork, the whole nine yards.  So now you're back in Gwyn and the loot is handled in the most inane, unfair and &quot;smoke filled room&quot; manner you've ever seen.  People are going to get mad and be really turned off - they won't trust you which means they likey won't come back.  No matter what success you had in the dungeon, the manner in which you handle the loot can make or break the raid (and potentially future raids).<br>
<br>
Knowing that, Shy and I intentionally talked a lot about loot policy - what did we think should be done and what had we seen done on other raids that seemed to work well.  We wanted the loot policy to be as simple and transparent as possible to minimize any feelings of unfairness.  We also wanted to explicitely lay out all of that policy for anyone to refer to at any time - again this promotes openness and keeps us accountable to what we said we'd do.  Given that, we do update our raid guidelines and loot policy when issues come up.  In fact, we actually need to add a bullet somewhere about spec stones and Apoc necklaces.  <br>
<br>
Even taking great pains to try and be as fair as possible to all involved, you will still find folks who disagree with all or a portion of your loot policy.  <br>
<br>
For me, I have a lot of fun in the challenge of how far we can get, how fast we can do it, can we get to the Horsemen, can we beat Apoc, how we work as a team, etc.  There are a lot of factors that can make a raid fun!  Loot is also one of those factors, moreso for some than others, but to some extent everyone is interested in the neat stuff that drops that they might be able to use.  I know I am.<br>
<br>
However, first and foremost you can't have a raid without people.  No matter how many board posts, emails and /msgs in game Shy and I send, if no one shows up then there is no raid.  It doesn't matter how organized we were.  So if people are essential for a raid to happen, then it follows that those same people all deserve a fair shot at the spoils of the raid.  By adhering to our own loot rules, I think Shy and I help to build our personal credibility (as well as the Alliance's).  We also build trust and fairness with the guilds we have invited, which means they'll want to come back again and again (which means more fun all around!!).<br>
<br>
I did want to be aware of Azrok's raids in case of a potential trainwreck, so thanks Vince for getting on the list.  I'm really looking forward to this Saturday!!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
